<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-03-27T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-03-27T20:00:00-05:00" n="269" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d269">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.11/499: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Mukden</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Sokobin</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Mukden</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-03-28T09:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">March 28,
                                        1927—9 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received March 28—6:08
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>I venture to suggest full publicity be given to the fact that Americans
                            in Manchuria are in nowise affected by the events in the Yangtze Valley;
                            situation here absolutely normal.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Sokobin</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>